// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// LANDING is DocumentKit's own module page, generated by the engine it documents. Reading
// `Landing.typeName` (`DocumentKitDemo/main.swift` writes it to `DocumentKit.docc/
// DocumentKit.md`, the module's doc-extension, title `` ``DocumentKit`` ``, merged onto
// the auto-generated module stub, never a second address) renders the intro prose, the mechanism
// reference, AND the gallery: one page, one build, no hand-authored duplicate kept in step by
// hand. Every gallery example below is a REAL composition, not a description of one. Reading
// this file's output is reading what the engine actually does.
//
// A category marker, local to this file: DocumentKit itself has no `Screen`/`Fragment`
// (those are Organization's naming, not the engine's: `Sources/Organization/View/
// Screen.swift`). `DocumentKit` depends on nothing, so it does not borrow them.
//
// Three attempts at a drawn, two-axis border (a table of pixel images, a text-drawn box, a
// wider table with an extra "island" column) were tried here and removed, kept only in
// SurfaceLaw §S15/§S19/§S20 as the record of why. All three tried to fake a second axis this
// render target does not have (no row-height primitive, GFM has no cell merging), and one
// depended on a monospace font this viewer does not guarantee. The one mechanism that survived
// every check is TEXT flowing on its default (`Gap`/`SpaceBetween`, below), so that is
// where the real richness lives now: not a drawn shape, a RULE TABLE.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

public protocol GallerySection: Open {}

/// This names the two labels every section repeats: a real call site (`Used like this:`), then
/// what it renders to (`Comes out like this:`), so a reader always knows which is which.
enum UsedLikeThisLabel: Close {}
extension UsedLikeThisLabel {
    static var typeName: String { "Used like this:" }
}
enum ComesOutLikeThisLabel: Close {}
extension ComesOutLikeThisLabel {
    static var typeName: String { "Comes out like this:" }
}

/// This stands in as a link target: `Gallery.self` would read `Gallery.typeName`, which reads
/// `Body.typeName`, which contains the very link reading `Gallery.typeName` again, infinite
/// recursion at the first render (checked directly, the same circularity `AliceUnlocked` avoids
/// by pointing at `SecretPage<...>` instead of itself). A real page would name a real other
/// page. This names an inert leaf, to demonstrate the syntax without depending on one existing.
/// No `typeName` override: `Close`'s inherited default (`Structure`'s, `String(describing:
/// Self.self)`) already reads "ExampleTarget," its real Swift name, so a demo link actually
/// resolves to this (empty, auto-generated) symbol page instead of dangling on a fictional one.
public enum ExampleTarget: Close {}

